00:05:40.840 --> 00:05:42.710
So connectivity.

00:05:42.710 --> 00:05:44.520
By the way, just
wanted to outline.

00:05:44.520 --> 00:05:47.890
This by no means just the best
practice for emerging markets.

00:05:47.890 --> 00:05:49.830
These are good practices
and good principles

00:05:49.830 --> 00:05:52.800
to implement even
for the users today.

00:05:52.800 --> 00:05:53.950
So connectivity.

00:05:53.950 --> 00:05:57.856
You want to assure smooth
loading of your content.

00:05:57.856 --> 00:05:59.730
You should prioritize
your bandwidth requests

00:05:59.730 --> 00:06:03.410
and make sure that the top
requests are served first.

00:06:03.410 --> 00:06:05.730
That the most useful
and relevant information

00:06:05.730 --> 00:06:07.230
is loaded at the beginning.

00:06:07.230 --> 00:06:10.410
For example, loading text
before you're loading images.

00:06:10.410 --> 00:06:13.110
Don't duplicate your
network requests,

00:06:13.110 --> 00:06:16.170
and save files locally
where applicable.

00:06:16.170 --> 00:06:18.930
You could use the Connectivity
Manager, which is actually

00:06:18.930 --> 00:06:21.240
a dynamic API that
gives you feedback

00:06:21.240 --> 00:06:26.220
on what kind of connectivity you
should expect from this device,

00:06:26.220 --> 00:06:29.820
and then change your
app serving accordingly.

00:06:29.820 --> 00:06:33.910
Images are typically the biggest
perpetrators of slow load

00:06:33.910 --> 00:06:35.550
time and slow connectivity.

00:06:35.550 --> 00:06:41.110
So I invite you to think about
the standards of the images you

00:06:41.110 --> 00:06:41.610
load.

00:06:41.610 --> 00:06:44.610
Which formats which
resolution you actually load,

00:06:44.610 --> 00:06:46.380
and where it becomes relevant.

00:06:46.380 --> 00:06:48.870
And make sure that you're
using the appropriate sizes

00:06:48.870 --> 00:06:51.390
of those images.

00:06:51.390 --> 00:06:53.540
Lastly, with regards
to connectivity,

00:06:53.540 --> 00:06:56.700
I encourage you all to look at
how your app and game performs

00:06:56.700 --> 00:06:58.380
in an offline environment.

00:06:58.380 --> 00:07:01.440
Just go ahead, turn your
phone into airplane mode.

00:07:01.440 --> 00:07:03.420
Open up your app and
see what happens.

00:07:03.420 --> 00:07:05.430
See where it
actually finds bugs.

00:07:05.430 --> 00:07:07.770
See where it actually
gets stuck and what

00:07:07.770 --> 00:07:11.190
experiences you need to improve
to assure a good offline

00:07:11.190 --> 00:07:13.890
experience.

00:07:13.890 --> 00:07:16.890
Moving on to device
compatibility.

00:07:16.890 --> 00:07:20.250
A huge range of devices with
big screens, small screens,

00:07:20.250 --> 00:07:23.520
expandable storage, small
storage, high-density screens,

00:07:23.520 --> 00:07:26.310
and so forth.

00:07:26.310 --> 00:07:31.230
I guess all of us face
the issue of developing

00:07:31.230 --> 00:07:32.670
an app and a game
that can really

00:07:32.670 --> 00:07:34.750
run on all of these devices.

00:07:34.750 --> 00:07:39.480
So you should look at what
capacity your app is actually

00:07:39.480 --> 00:07:41.820
invoking, and then
optimize for that.

00:07:41.820 --> 00:07:44.280
Keep in mind that a lot of
these devices that we're

00:07:44.280 --> 00:07:47.580
talking about are still 1
megabyte in RAM and below.

00:07:47.580 --> 00:07:51.000
So you should think about
how your app actually runs

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:52.540
in these kind of environments.

00:07:52.540 --> 00:07:55.260
And games should be
optimized to render smoothly

00:07:55.260 --> 00:08:00.060
in those kinds of environments.

00:08:00.060 --> 00:08:01.110
Look at screen sizes.

00:08:01.110 --> 00:08:05.420
As I mentioned, these
devices that are coming on

00:08:05.420 --> 00:08:06.930
are likely to be low cost.

00:08:06.930 --> 00:08:11.250
They are likely to be
longer in their lifecycles.

00:08:11.250 --> 00:08:14.130
And you want to make sure that
you have your exposure tested

00:08:14.130 --> 00:08:16.620
on different screen
sizes, screen resolution,

00:08:16.620 --> 00:08:19.005
and pixel densities.

00:08:19.005 --> 00:08:23.090
[INAUDIBLE] mentioned
before that the new emulator

00:08:23.090 --> 00:08:25.650
in Android Studio
is vastly improved.

00:08:25.650 --> 00:08:28.620
It's increased in speed and it
allows you to test very quickly

00:08:28.620 --> 00:08:29.610
for these elements.

00:08:29.610 --> 00:08:32.820
So changing the device
resolution and the device size.

00:08:32.820 --> 00:08:36.240
Just as an example, why would
you load high-resolution image

00:08:36.240 --> 00:08:37.909
on a low-resolution device?

00:08:37.909 --> 00:08:43.785
That's just a lot of waste
in many different factors.

00:08:43.785 --> 00:08:47.104
Moving on to efficient
memory usage.

00:08:47.104 --> 00:08:48.520
Users see that
screen at all time.

00:08:48.520 --> 00:08:50.190
They can get a push
notification when

00:08:50.190 --> 00:08:51.600
their memory is running out.

00:08:51.600 --> 00:08:53.970
And they can actually
see a sorted list

00:08:53.970 --> 00:08:57.960
of how much memory and
how much storage your apps

00:08:57.960 --> 00:09:00.660
are actually using.

00:09:00.660 --> 00:09:02.430
So here's the pro
tip for this one.

00:09:02.430 --> 00:09:05.070
You can use the API
call of is low RAM

00:09:05.070 --> 00:09:07.950
and actually get
feedback in real time

00:09:07.950 --> 00:09:10.470
to figure out if this is
a highly-capable device

00:09:10.470 --> 00:09:11.940
or a low-capable device.

00:09:11.940 --> 00:09:14.770
And then, change your
processes accordingly.

00:09:14.770 --> 00:09:16.590
Also, background processing.

00:09:16.590 --> 00:09:18.270
Background processing
is typically

00:09:18.270 --> 00:09:23.790
what drives up a lot of the
storage on the user's device.

00:09:23.790 --> 00:09:25.240
And that's perfectly fine.

00:09:25.240 --> 00:09:28.260
Many apps may invoke
processes in the background,

00:09:28.260 --> 00:09:32.790
but you should be good stewards
of your user's device memory.

00:09:32.790 --> 00:09:35.400
And so you want to start up
your background processes,

00:09:35.400 --> 00:09:37.870
finish them, try to bundle
them into one round,

00:09:37.870 --> 00:09:40.380
and then shut down the
process in order not

00:09:40.380 --> 00:09:45.570
to drain the user's memory
as well as the battery.

00:09:45.570 --> 00:09:47.160
Moving on to smart storage.

00:09:47.160 --> 00:09:50.310
Think about installing or just
running this one line of code

00:09:50.310 --> 00:09:54.660
that allows users to push
their apps onto their SD card.

00:09:54.660 --> 00:09:56.730
This can go a long
way for devices

00:09:56.730 --> 00:09:58.950
with expandable storage.

00:09:58.950 --> 00:10:00.780
As I mentioned before,
users can actually

00:10:00.780 --> 00:10:04.890
sort how much data is
consumed and how much space

00:10:04.890 --> 00:10:07.590
is consumed on
your phone and can

00:10:07.590 --> 00:10:12.040
see the list of the most
draining apps on top, which

00:10:12.040 --> 00:10:16.200
will then drive a lot of the
uninstalls, uninstall rates up.

00:10:16.200 --> 00:10:20.250
So you want to keep your device
consumption low and make sure

00:10:20.250 --> 00:10:25.710
that you are frequently clearing
the cache that you're creating.

00:10:25.710 --> 00:10:28.870
This one is a tip that
I'm sure you're not

00:10:28.870 --> 00:10:30.730
going to hear often today.

00:10:30.730 --> 00:10:32.447
So this is the
one and only time,

00:10:32.447 --> 00:10:33.780
I guess, you will hear us today.

00:10:33.780 --> 00:10:36.720
But think about
backwards compatibility.

00:10:36.720 --> 00:10:39.370
Think about these
new users coming

00:10:39.370 --> 00:10:41.400
online with slightly
older devices

00:10:41.400 --> 00:10:44.740
and not necessarily always on
the latest version of Android.

00:10:44.740 --> 00:10:50.070
So I'd invite you to run your
apps with the minimum SDK 14,

00:10:50.070 --> 00:10:52.750
but target SDK 23 in
order to really cater

00:10:52.750 --> 00:10:57.450
to a wide variety of users that
are being kept with the latest

00:10:57.450 --> 00:10:58.410
features.

00:10:58.410 --> 00:11:01.480
Also, think about integrating
the Google Play Services

00:11:01.480 --> 00:11:05.450
API because it will ensure that
the users get updates on time.

00:11:05.450 --> 00:11:08.460
And we will make sure that
the users are catered to

00:11:08.460 --> 00:11:13.170
with the features that actually
work for their devices.

00:11:13.170 --> 00:11:15.810
Moving on, and I'm
