00:11:20.700 --> 00:11:22.260
I'm looking at data costs.

00:11:22.260 --> 00:11:25.320
As we said before, data is
expensive in these countries.

00:11:25.320 --> 00:11:28.120
And it's only very
slowly becoming cheaper.

00:11:28.120 --> 00:11:30.820
We're used to having
cheap, always-on data.

00:11:30.820 --> 00:11:33.510
But the reality is
about half of users

00:11:33.510 --> 00:11:35.640
don't have that privilege today.

00:11:35.640 --> 00:11:38.430
Installing your app is an
actual cost to the user.

00:11:38.430 --> 00:11:42.780
And think about how sizable
your APK actually is.

00:11:42.780 --> 00:11:45.720
How much space and
how much data usage

00:11:45.720 --> 00:11:47.730
the user's actually
going to consume

00:11:47.730 --> 00:11:49.470
by just downloading your app.

00:11:49.470 --> 00:11:52.200
If you have a prepaid package
for 200 megabytes a month,

00:11:52.200 --> 00:11:54.330
how likely are you to
actually download a game that

00:11:54.330 --> 00:11:57.990
is 100 megabytes on free data?

00:11:57.990 --> 00:12:01.940
So again, think
about your APK size.

00:12:01.940 --> 00:12:04.440
And there is a great talk from
Google I/O, which I encourage

00:12:04.440 --> 00:12:05.356
you to take a look at.

00:12:05.356 --> 00:12:07.830
It's called "Put
Your APK on a Diet."

00:12:07.830 --> 00:12:09.610
Definitely, worth checking out.

00:12:09.610 --> 00:12:13.620
The sweet spot for emerging
markets is around 10 megabytes.

00:12:13.620 --> 00:12:15.180
That's what you
should be aiming for.

00:12:15.180 --> 00:12:17.430
We see a high drop-off
with every megabyte

00:12:17.430 --> 00:12:18.747
that you add in weight.

00:12:18.747 --> 00:12:21.330
Now, we realize for a lot of the
game developers in this room,

00:12:21.330 --> 00:12:24.000
this number is
completely unreasonable.

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:28.757
Building a high-quality 3D game
in 10 megabytes is very tricky.

00:12:28.757 --> 00:12:30.465
And oftentimes, the
third-party libraries

00:12:30.465 --> 00:12:32.790
you're using on
their own are already

00:12:32.790 --> 00:12:34.630
exceeding those 10 megabytes.

00:12:34.630 --> 00:12:37.260
So if you can't make
this number work,

00:12:37.260 --> 00:12:39.510
and this number sounds
completely unreasonable to you,

00:12:39.510 --> 00:12:41.490
consider multi-APK.

00:12:41.490 --> 00:12:44.640
Launching multiple APKs into
different device categories

00:12:44.640 --> 00:12:48.400
just to make sure that you can
cater to those users as well.

00:12:48.400 --> 00:12:51.720
So again, users are
sensitive to APK sizes.

00:12:51.720 --> 00:12:54.000
Images, as we noted before,
are the biggest offenders

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:54.750
with this.

00:12:54.750 --> 00:12:56.860
You want to reduce
costs, and you

00:12:56.860 --> 00:13:00.390
want to consider
multi-APK to serve this.

00:13:00.390 --> 00:13:03.450
Again, Android Studio
and Firebase Analytics

00:13:03.450 --> 00:13:06.105
allows you to test and
see how much data your app

00:13:06.105 --> 00:13:07.620
is actually consuming.

00:13:07.620 --> 00:13:09.880
You can benchmark the data.

00:13:09.880 --> 00:13:13.420
And being, again, good
stewards of this data

00:13:13.420 --> 00:13:15.750
will go a long way
with the users.

00:13:15.750 --> 00:13:17.770
Moving to battery consumption.

00:13:17.770 --> 00:13:19.980
You want to eliminate
unnecessary wake-ups.

00:13:19.980 --> 00:13:23.760
You want to batch your network
requests whenever they come in.

00:13:23.760 --> 00:13:26.611
And you want to use the
Network Manager API.

00:13:26.611 --> 00:13:28.360
Again, which can give
you feedback on what

00:13:28.360 --> 00:13:31.920
kind of network is expected.

00:13:31.920 --> 00:13:33.450
Moving on to content.

00:13:33.450 --> 00:13:35.970
Users everywhere want
tailored content.

00:13:35.970 --> 00:13:38.070
We know this from our own data.

00:13:38.070 --> 00:13:39.480
When we're looking
at Google Play

00:13:39.480 --> 00:13:42.810
and we optimize it for
different scenarios,

00:13:42.810 --> 00:13:45.960
highlighting and surfacing
specific tailored content

00:13:45.960 --> 00:13:49.020
for a local audience, we
see significant improvements

00:13:49.020 --> 00:13:51.850
in adoption and engagement.

00:13:51.850 --> 00:13:53.640
So localization is important.

00:13:53.640 --> 00:13:55.710
Think about fast,
responsive of UIs.

00:13:55.710 --> 00:13:58.870
Think about the UI best
practices, which we talked

00:13:58.870 --> 00:14:00.290
about today in material design.

00:14:02.990 --> 00:14:06.340
These are all best
practices to really cater

00:14:06.340 --> 00:14:09.340
to a user in a
local environment.

00:14:09.340 --> 00:14:10.800
To make sure that
they feel at home

00:14:10.800 --> 00:14:12.591
and that they feel that
this environment is

00:14:12.591 --> 00:14:15.230
tailored for their use.

00:14:15.230 --> 00:14:17.390
Last but not least, commerce.

00:14:17.390 --> 00:14:20.360
We all strive to make this a
business and not just a fun

00:14:20.360 --> 00:14:21.350
exercise.

00:14:21.350 --> 00:14:23.405
So catering to those markets.

00:14:23.405 --> 00:14:26.390
You want to adjust your
monetization strategy

00:14:26.390 --> 00:14:27.680
accordingly.

00:14:27.680 --> 00:14:29.990
There's multiple different
ways of driving revenue

00:14:29.990 --> 00:14:31.190
from these markets.

00:14:31.190 --> 00:14:33.950
Obviously, users are
more sensitive to price.

00:14:33.950 --> 00:14:39.380
But you want to use multiple
different monetization schemes

00:14:39.380 --> 00:14:41.402
to really figure
out what works best.

00:14:41.402 --> 00:14:42.860
Some of which might
be best catered

00:14:42.860 --> 00:14:46.040
to with in-app purchases while
other markets are specifically

00:14:46.040 --> 00:14:48.270
more susceptible to ad revenue.

00:14:48.270 --> 00:14:52.340
So when driving
different ways, we

00:14:52.340 --> 00:14:55.490
want to make Google Play a
commerce platform for you

00:14:55.490 --> 00:15:01.380
and enable good businesses
in those regions as well.

00:15:01.380 --> 00:15:03.984
So think about the
barrier of entry.

00:15:03.984 --> 00:15:05.150
Where do you want to charge?

00:15:05.150 --> 00:15:07.640
At what levels and
what price points do

00:15:07.640 --> 00:15:10.070
you want to charge
for your content?

00:15:10.070 --> 00:15:12.860
And offer prices
in local currency.

00:15:12.860 --> 00:15:16.490
We've just referred to earlier
about pricing templates.

00:15:16.490 --> 00:15:17.965
I encourage you to use those.

00:15:17.965 --> 00:15:19.340
And to make sure
that your prices

00:15:19.340 --> 00:15:23.450
are adjusted in the local
currency at the right numbers.

00:15:23.450 --> 00:15:25.790
And in addition to that,
you should also take a look

00:15:25.790 --> 00:15:27.770
at the Big Mac
index, the purchasing

00:15:27.770 --> 00:15:30.590
power of a single dollar
in a single country.

00:15:30.590 --> 00:15:32.600
If you multiplied
that with the prices

00:15:32.600 --> 00:15:34.400
you're actually charging,
you automatically

00:15:34.400 --> 00:15:36.860
become more sensible
to that local market

00:15:36.860 --> 00:15:38.420
because you're
charging something

00:15:38.420 --> 00:15:43.400
that is actually equivalent
to what users can afford.

00:15:43.400 --> 00:15:46.200
So I'm summarizing the
points we've made earlier.

00:15:46.200 --> 00:15:48.080
And again, there's
a lot of resources

00:15:48.080 --> 00:15:51.080
which I'll share
after Hugo's talk

00:15:51.080 --> 00:15:53.990
on how to really look
at these best practices,

00:15:53.990 --> 00:15:55.820
figure out which ones
are relevant for you,

00:15:55.820 --> 00:15:57.560
and then go out
and implement them.

00:15:57.560 --> 00:16:00.650
But if there's three main
pieces of information

00:16:00.650 --> 00:16:04.280
that I would like to share today
